𝐃𝐚𝐲 𝟏𝟎 – 𝐋𝐞𝐚𝐫𝐧 𝐆𝐞𝐫𝐦𝐚𝐧 𝐀𝟏 𝐰𝐢𝐭𝐡 𝐌𝐞: 𝐆𝐞𝐫𝐦𝐚𝐧 𝐏𝐫𝐨𝐧𝐨𝐮𝐧𝐬 𝐚𝐧𝐝 𝐕𝐞𝐫𝐛 𝐂𝐨𝐧𝐣𝐮𝐠𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧𝐬 😇 

Today, let’s get comfortable with essential German pronouns and how verbs change when paired with them.

✅ 𝐊𝐞𝐲 𝐏𝐫𝐨𝐧𝐨𝐮𝐧𝐬 𝐚𝐧𝐝 𝐓𝐡𝐞𝐢𝐫 𝐌𝐞𝐚𝐧𝐢𝐧𝐠𝐬:
Ich - I (First person singular)
Sie - You (formal, singular and plural)
du - you (informal, singular)
These are the most common pronouns you'll use when starting out!

✅ 𝐕𝐞𝐫𝐛 𝐄𝐧𝐝𝐢𝐧𝐠𝐬 𝐚𝐭 𝐚 𝐆𝐥𝐚𝐧𝐜𝐞:
When conjugating regular verbs, the ending changes based on the pronoun:
- For ich, the verb ending is typically -e.
 Example: Ich heiße (I am called), Ich wohne (I live), Ich komme (I come)
- For du, the verb ending is typically -st.
 Example: Du heißt (You are called), Du wohnst (You live), Du kommst (You come)
- For Sie (formal You), the verb ending is typically -en.
 Example: Sie heißen (You are called), Sie wohnen (You live), Sie kommen (You come)

✅ 𝐂𝐨𝐧𝐣𝐮𝐠𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 𝐄𝐱𝐚𝐦𝐩𝐥𝐞𝐬:
Let’s look at some common verbs and their conjugations with these pronouns:

1. heißen (to be called)
Ich heiße Martin. (I am called Martin.)
Wie heißt du? (What are you called?)
Wie heißen Sie? (What are you called? - formal)

2. wohnen (to live)
Ich wohne in Berlin. (I live in Berlin.)
Wo wohnst du? (Where do you live? - informal)
Wo wohnen Sie? (Where do you live? - formal)

3. kommen (to come)
Ich komme aus Deutschland. (I come from Germany.)
Woher kommst du? (Where do you come from? - informal)
Woher kommen Sie? (Where do you come from? - formal)

✍️ 𝐏𝐫𝐚𝐜𝐭𝐢𝐜𝐞 𝐓𝐢𝐩: Choose any of the verbs above and try to form sentences using ich, du, and Sie.
📌 Example with "lernen" (to learn):
Ich lerne Deutsch. (I am learning German.)
Du lernst Deutsch. (You are learning German.)
Sie lernen Deutsch. (You are learning German - formal.)

Keep practicing these conjugations; they are the backbone of German conversation! 🌱

✨ Share your own conjugated sentences in the comments if you’d like me to review them!
